<section xml:id="sec_solving_equations_in_maple">
  <title>Solving Equations in Maple</title>
  <subsection>
    <title>Recommended Tutorials:</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          \nameref{chp:equation_solvers}, pg.
          <xref ref="chp_equation_solvers"></xref>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction:</title>
    <p>
      In this activity,
      students will be asked to assign expressions and then evaluate and manipulate them.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises:</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Suppose we want to find the <m>x</m>-intercepts of the function
          <me>
            f(x) = x^5+x^4-4x^3-3x^2+3x+1
          </me>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Assign the function to <m>f(x)</m>.
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    When assigning the function to <m>f(x)</m>,
                    use the <m>:=</m> operator.
                  </p>
                </aside>
            <idx><h>assignment operator</h></idx>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Plot <m>f(x)</m>.
                Choose an interval for <m>x</m> that shows all <m>x</m>-intercepts.
                How many do you see?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Factor <m>f(x)</m>.
                Does <m>f(x)</m> factor?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Solve <m>f(x)=0</m> using both the <c>solve()</c> and <c>fsolve()</c> commands.
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    With <c>fsolve()</c>,
                    you can also specify an interval for solutions if you wish to only find a particular solution.
                    An example of this can be found on <xref ref="eg_fsolve_interval">page</xref>.
                  </p>
                </aside>
            <idx><h>solving equations</h><h>solve</h></idx>
            <idx><h>solving equations</h><h>fsolve</h></idx>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Solve the quadratic equation <m>x^2+4x+6=0</m> three ways:
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Using the quadratic formula by hand.
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    Given a quadratic equation of the form
                    <m>ax^2+bx+c=0</m>, the quadratic formula is
                    <me>
                      x=\dfrac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </aside>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Using <c>solve()</c>,
                followed by evaluating the result as a decimal.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Using <c>fsolve()</c>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        Compare your results from (b) and (c).
        <aside>
          <p>
            In Maple, <m>\sqrt{-1}</m> is denoted as <m>I</m>.
          </p>
        </aside>
            <idx><h>imaginary</h></idx>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Consider the curves <m>y=x^2</m> and <m>y=\frac{3}{x}</m>.
          <aside>
            <p>
              An example that shows how to find the intersection point of two functions is given on <xref ref="subsec_functionintersection">page</xref>.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the point <m>(x,y)</m> where the two curves intersect.
                Try using both the <c>solve()</c> and <c>fsolve()</c> commands.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Plot the two curves on the same set of axes to verify that your intersection point from part (a) is correct.
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    When plotting equations of the form <m>y=f(x)</m> using the <c>plot()</c> command,
                    we never include the <m>y=</m>.
                  </p>
                </aside>
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    When multiple curves are plotted on the same set of axes,
                    it is a good practice to specify the colour of each one,
                    so that you can tell them apart.
                  </p>
                </aside>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
</section>